<subsection xml:id="subsec-volume-in-real-life" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Volume in Real Life</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction xml:id="auto_rlpvwfb4">
            <dl>
                <li xml:id="auto_y5665tfh">
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_5ef65zg7">
                        2.0 Measurements and Geometry
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_k9brsggc">
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_occsc4vv">
                        2.8 Volume
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_jhvzy3bc">
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_38oxdocf">
                        Apply volume formulas to solve real-life problems involving storage, transport, and household needs.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_n9k1jlnm" component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_91abau0v">
                        10
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_eag4v29g" component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_h0czxmrs">
                        40 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
            <p xml:id="auto_0rjys64e" component="lesson-plan">
                <p xml:id="auto_n4eo7ffn"> Upon completion of this lesson, learners will be able to:
                <ol>
                    <li xml:id="auto_9wp92gaf">
                        <p xml:id="auto_c9o7kalx">
                            <alert>Know (Conceptual Understanding):</alert> Understand that volume measures how much a container holds and that different shapes require different formulas. Know how to convert between cubic metres and litres (<m>1\,\text{m}^3 = 1000\,\text{L}</m>).
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_tq1rosbf">
                        <p xml:id="auto_lplghpsc">
                            <alert>Do (Procedural Skill):</alert> Identify container shapes, convert measurements to consistent units, apply the appropriate volume formula, and convert the result to litres. Apply a step-by-step process: identify shape, convert units, apply formula, convert to litres.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_4vrec3ig">
                        <p xml:id="auto_ychws36p">
                            <alert>Apply (Application/Problem-Solving):</alert> Solve real-life problems involving storage (water tanks, grain stores), transport (jerrycans, drums), household needs (pots, containers), farming (irrigation), and construction (concrete, materials).
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
                </p>
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </objectives>
    <axiom component="resources">
        <!-- Link to blurb -->
        <xi:include href="../../resources-blurb-lesson.ptx" />

        <sbsgroup widths="45% 45%" margins="2% 2%">
            <sidebyside>
                <p xml:id="auto_j78mw2lz">
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/volume/volume-in-real-life.pdf"> Lesson Plan </dataurl>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_63by5wi6">
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/volume/step-by-step-guide_volume-in-real-life.pdf"> Step-by-Step Guide </dataurl>
                </p>
            </sidebyside>
        </sbsgroup>
    </axiom>
    <xi:include href="../../resources-materials.ptx" />


    <introduction xml:id="auto_5788600b">
        <p xml:id="auto_7s23oacx">
           <alert> Volume</alert> tells us how much space an object or container holds. In everyday life we use volume to know how much water fits in a jerrycan, how much grain a sack will carry, or how much fuel a drum can store. Knowing how to calculate volume helps families and communities measure and plan for storage, transport and household needs, and it is useful in farming, construction and cooking.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_3ipxt9q7">
            In this section we practice simple formulas for common shapes (box, cylinder, cone) and learn to convert between litres and cubic metres so the results are useful in ordinary situations.
        </p>
    </introduction>


    <activity xml:id="auto_jcdvpkhk">
        <statement>
            <ul>
                <li xml:id="auto_1lxadd8f">
                    <p xml:id="auto_50cv6q0i">
                        Think about different containers you might find in school or at home, and that you might want to carry water or store flour in.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_mu9oalek">
                    <p xml:id="auto_52dvsfvu">
                        For example, this could include jars, barrels, boxes, ...
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_pt2cpvqg">
                    <p xml:id="auto_0n6meumo">
                        For each, determine what kind of shape it is and estimate its dimensions. Try to compute its volume.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_66zdjoqi">
                    <p xml:id="auto_67h2emny">
                        Which of these containers can store the largest amount of water or flour?
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </statement>
    </activity>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 2: Formalizing Volume in Real Life</title>
        <dl>
            <li xml:id="auto_wh3mhc6a">
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_3e4s5h4i">
                    10 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_zc3fplu9">
                <title>Grouping</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_amy3dgkp">
                    Whole class
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_ch2nx9q7">
                <title>Key Teaching Points</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_rsapmdto">
                    Formalise the step-by-step process for volume problems:
                    <ol marker="1.">
                        <li xml:id="auto_sj7gi0cg"><p xml:id="auto_doxxmtig">Identify the shape of the container.</p></li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_exdnmdnw"><p xml:id="auto_w478yi1x">Convert all measurements to the same unit (usually metres).</p></li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_zky5kdpo"><p xml:id="auto_iitk3vu6">Apply the appropriate volume formula.</p></li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_azjc96xf"><p xml:id="auto_ntwnll6s">Calculate volume in cubic metres.</p></li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_ew3m1kus"><p xml:id="auto_8sbhvrc8">Convert to litres by multiplying by 1000.</p></li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_hjp1cwk4">
                <title>Common Formulas Reference</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_b0qdkudp">
                    <tabular halign="left">
                        <row header="yes" bottom="minor">
                            <cell>Shape</cell>
                            <cell>Formula</cell>
                            <cell>Real-Life Example</cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell>Rectangular Box</cell>
                            <cell><m>V = l \times w \times h</m></cell>
                            <cell>Jerrycan, storage box</cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell>Cylinder</cell>
                            <cell><m>V = \pi r^2 h</m></cell>
                            <cell>Drum, water tank, pipe</cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell>Cone</cell>
                            <cell><m>V = \frac{1}{3}\pi r^2 h</m></cell>
                            <cell>Borehole, funnel, grain pile</cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell>Sphere</cell>
                            <cell><m>V = \frac{4}{3}\pi r^3</m></cell>
                            <cell>Water tank, ball</cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell>Triangular Prism</cell>
                            <cell><m>V = \frac{1}{2}bh \times l</m></cell>
                            <cell>Roof storage, attic</cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell>Pyramid</cell>
                            <cell><m>V = \frac{1}{3}Bh</m></cell>
                            <cell>Roof, grain storage</cell>
                        </row>
                    </tabular>
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_wujrkwng">
                <title>Scaffolding Strategies</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_2odplqhl">
                    <ul>
                        <li xml:id="auto_zawsfur5"><p xml:id="auto_4w04zkdn">Provide a reference chart with formulas for each shape.</p></li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_2yluaeg1"><p xml:id="auto_6aobdjdm">Emphasise unit conversion as a separate step: cm <m>\to</m> m (divide by 100).</p></li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_lc3kabkh"><p xml:id="auto_4374oc8q">Show that <m>1\,\text{m}^3 = 1000\,\text{L}</m> using a cube diagram.</p></li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_cpbxqe64"><p xml:id="auto_0cepnzr5">Connect formulas to shape properties (why <m>\pi r^2</m> for circles).</p></li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </axiom>
<insight xml:id="auto_gayd79f9">
        <title>Volume in Everyday Life</title>
        <ul>
            <li xml:id="auto_l38nfvob">
                Volume measures how much a container holds; use formulas for boxes and cylinders for common containers.
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_x1l8xcw7">
                Always use consistent units: convert centimetres to metres before computing volume, then convert cubic metres to litres by multiplying by 1000.
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_t4v96tqq">
                Estimating volumes helps with storage, transport, planning for water and grain, and with simple cost calculations in rural and urban settings alike.
            </li>
        </ul>
    </insight>
    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 3: Practice and Application</title>
        <dl>
            <li xml:id="auto_twylcdv5">
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_c54qqffi">
                    15 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_z5wa0e1f">
                <title>Grouping</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_yqnw0g7t">
                    Individual, then pairs for checking
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_xndml7x8">
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_p6clrkk6">
                    Walk through Examples 1<ndash/>3 on the board, emphasising the step-by-step process: identify shape, convert units, apply formula, convert to litres. Then allow students to attempt the remaining examples and exercises independently.
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </axiom>

    <example xml:id="ex-jerrycan-volume">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_z852cpie">
                A metal jerrycan is roughly a rectangular box of dimensions 35 cm by 20 cm by 30 cm. Estimate how many litres of water it can hold.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <paragraphs>
                <title>Compute the Volume</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_5p5fdklu">
                    Volume of a box is <m>V = lwh</m>. Convert centimetres to metres: <m>l=0.35\,m,\; w=0.20\,m,\; h=0.30\,m.</m>
                    Thus <m>V = 0.35\times0.20\times0.30 = 0.021\,\text{m}^3.</m>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_oy30xfn9">
                    Convert cubic metres to litres: <m>1\,\text{m}^3 = 1000\,\text{L}</m>, so <m>V = 0.021\times1000 = 21\,\text{L}.</m>
                </p>
            </paragraphs>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="ex-water-drum-cylinder">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_i5jxvdkw">
                A cylindrical water drum has radius 0.25 m and height 1.0 m. Find its volume in litres.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p xml:id="auto_losbq9sd">
                Volume of a cylinder: <m>V=\pi r^2 h.</m> So <m>V=\pi\times(0.25)^2\times1.0\approx\pi\times0.0625\approx0.19635\,\text{m}^3.</m>
                In litres: <m>0.19635\times1000\approx196\,\text{L}.</m>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="ex-cone-borehole">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_xuxuselw">
                A small borehole is shaped like a cone with height 1.2 m and base radius 0.15 m. Estimate the volume of water it can hold in litres.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p xml:id="auto_fdh0tcxs">Volume of a cone: <m>V=\tfrac{1}{3}\pi r^2 h</m>. So <m>V=\tfrac{1}{3}\pi(0.15)^2(1.2)\approx\tfrac{1}{3}\pi\times0.027\approx0.0283\,\text{m}^3</m>, which is about <m>28\,\text{L}.</m></p>
        </solution>
    </example>


        <example xml:id="ex-vol-triangular-prism-roof">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_iiwdri2n">
                    The storage space under a roof forms a triangular prism. The triangular cross-section has base 4 m and height 1.2 m, and the attic runs 6 m along the house. Estimate the storage volume in cubic metres and litres.
                </p>
                <image width="50%">
                    <shortdescription>Triangular prism roof</shortdescription>
                    <latex-image>
                        \tdplotsetmaincoords{75}{110}

                        \begin{tikzpicture}[tdplot_main_coords, scale=0.8]
                            % Dimensions: 
                            % Width (x) = 4m (-2 to 2)
                            % Length (y) = 6m (0 to 6)
                            % Height (z) = 1.2m
                            
                            % Front Face Vertices
                            \coordinate (F1) at (-2,0,0);
                            \coordinate (F2) at (2,0,0);
                            \coordinate (F_peak) at (0,0,1.2);
                            
                            % Back Face Vertices
                            \coordinate (B1) at (-2,6,0);
                            \coordinate (B2) at (2,6,0);
                            \coordinate (B_peak) at (0,6,1.2);

                            % Draw Hidden Lines (Back base)
                            \draw[dashed, gray] (B1) -- (B2);
                            \draw[dashed, gray] (F1) -- (B1);

                            % Draw the Floor
                            \fill[gray!10, opacity=0.5] (F1) -- (F2) -- (B2) -- (B1) -- cycle;
                            \draw[thick] (F1) -- (F2) -- (B2);

                            % Draw Gable Ends
                            \draw[thick, fill=brown!20, fill opacity=0.3] (F1) -- (F2) -- (F_peak) -- cycle;
                            \draw[thick] (B1) -- (B_peak) -- (B2);

                            % Draw Ridge Line (The Peak)
                            \draw[thick, orange!80!black] (F_peak) -- (B_peak);
                            
                            % Draw Slanted Roof Edges
                            \draw[thick] (F1) -- (B1); % Side edge
                            \draw[thick] (F2) -- (B2); % Side edge

                            % Dimensions Labels
                            \draw[&lt;-&gt;] (-2,-0.5,0) -- (2,-0.5,0) node[midway, below] {4m};
                            \draw[&lt;-&gt;] (2.5,0,0) -- (2.5,6,0) node[midway, right] {6m};
                            \draw[&lt;-&gt;, red] (0,0,0) -- (0,0,1.2) node[midway, left] {1.2m};

                        \end{tikzpicture}

                    </latex-image>
                </image>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p xml:id="auto_7sk03v1q">
                    Area of triangle = <m>\tfrac{1}{2}bh = 0.5\times4\times1.2 = 2.4\,\text{m}^2</m>. Volume = area × length = <m>2.4\times6 = 14.4\,\text{m}^3</m>, which is <m>14{,}400\,\text{L}.</m>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>

    <example xml:id="ex-composite-stack">
        <title>Composite Solid: Cylinder with Cone Top</title>
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_nmuxsgs3">
                A container is made by placing a cone (height 0.5 m, base radius 0.3 m) on top of a cylinder (height 1.0 m, same radius 0.3 m). Find the total volume in litres.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p xml:id="auto_abchhg5g">Cylinder: <m>V_c=\pi r^2 h=\pi\times0.3^2\times1.0=\pi\times0.09\approx0.283\,\text{m}^3.</m></p>
            <p xml:id="auto_8dgnhvz8">Cone: <m>V_k=\tfrac{1}{3}\pi r^2 h=\tfrac{1}{3}\pi\times0.09\times0.5=0.015\pi\approx0.047\,\text{m}^3.</m></p>
            <p xml:id="auto_7noqbcn6">Total: <m>0.283+0.047\approx0.330\,\text{m}^3\approx330\,\text{L}.</m></p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="ex-pyramidal-frustum-pond">
        <title>Pond</title>
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_ws31rbm3">
                A shallow pond is shaped like a frustum of a square pyramid. The water surface is a square 12 m by 12 m, the bottom is a square 6 m by 6 m, and the depth is 1.5 m. Estimate the volume of water in the pond in cubic metres and litres.
            </p>
            <image width="60%">
                <shortdescription>Pyramidal frustum pond</shortdescription>
                <latex-image>
                    \tdplotsetmaincoords{70}{20}

                    \begin{tikzpicture}[tdplot_main_coords, scale=0.5]
                        % Define Dimensions (scaled for visibility)
                        % Bottom square (6x6) -&gt; coordinates -3 to 3
                        % Top square (12x12) -&gt; coordinates -6 to 6
                        % Height 1.5
                        
                        % Vertices - Bottom
                        \coordinate (B1) at (-3,-3,0);
                        \coordinate (B2) at (3,-3,0);
                        \coordinate (B3) at (3,3,0);
                        \coordinate (B4) at (-3,3,0);
                        
                        % Vertices - Top
                        \coordinate (T1) at (-6,-6,3);
                        \coordinate (T2) at (6,-6,3);
                        \coordinate (T3) at (6,6,3);
                        \coordinate (T4) at (-6,6,3);

                        % Draw Bottom Base (dashed for hidden lines)
                        \draw[thick, dashed] (B1) -- (B2) -- (B3) -- (B4) -- cycle;

                        % Draw Water (Blue fill with transparency)
                        \fill[blue!20, opacity=0.6] (T1) -- (T2) -- (T3) -- (T4) -- cycle;

                        % Draw Slanted Edges
                        \draw[thick] (B1) -- (T1);
                        \draw[thick] (B2) -- (T2);
                        \draw[thick] (B3) -- (T3);
                        \draw[thick] (B4) -- (T4);

                        % Draw Top Rim
                        \draw[thick, blue!80!black] (T1) -- (T2) -- (T3) -- (T4) -- cycle;

                        % Annotations
                        \draw[&lt;-&gt;] (-6,-7,3) -- (6,-7,3) node[midway, below] {12m};
                        \draw[&lt;-&gt;] (-3,-4,0) -- (3,-4,0) node[midway, below] {6m};
                        \draw[&lt;-&gt;, red] (7,6,0) -- (7,6,3) node[midway, right] {h = 1.5m};

                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
            </image>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p xml:id="auto_tafbyfr7">
                For a pyramidal frustum the volume is <m>V=\tfrac{h}{3}(A_1 + A_2 + \sqrt{A_1A_2})</m> where <m>A_1</m> and <m>A_2</m> are the areas of the top and bottom squares. Here <m>A_1=12^2=144</m> and <m>A_2=6^2=36</m>, so <m>\sqrt{A_1A_2}=\sqrt{144\times36}=72</m>. Thus
                <m>V=\tfrac{1.5}{3}(144+36+72)=0.5\times252=126\,\text{m}^3</m>, which is about <m>126{,}000\,\text{L}.</m>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

