    </axiom>

    <exercises xml:id="exercises-volume-real-life">
        <title>Exercises</title>

        <exercise xml:id="ex-vol-grain-trough">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_tgaum5c9">
                    A farmer fills a rectangular trough 2.0 m long, 0.5 m wide and 0.4 m deep with water. How many litres of water does the trough hold?
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p xml:id="auto_eok4jsqw">400 L</p>
            </answer>
            <solution>
                <p xml:id="auto_b29z26fq">Volume: <m>2.0\times0.5\times0.4=0.4\,\text{m}^3</m>. In litres: <m>0.4\times1000=400\,\text{L}.</m></p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="ex-vol-water-drum">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_a0wmrjwq">
                    A drum has radius 0.30 m and height 0.9 m. Estimate its capacity in litres. (Use <m>\pi\approx3.14</m>.)
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p xml:id="auto_e6bnnijg">About 254 L</p>
            </answer>
            <solution>
                <p xml:id="auto_ge1h0krv">Volume: <m>V=\pi r^2 h = 3.14\times0.3^2\times0.9 = 3.14\times0.09\times0.9 \approx 0.254\,\text{m}^3</m>. In litres: <m>0.254\times1000\approx254\,\text{L}.</m></p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="ex-sphere-tank">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_nnyf7umw">
                    A spherical water tank has diameter 1.2 m. How many litres can it hold? (Use <m>\pi\approx3.14</m>.)
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p xml:id="auto_3d9x4zk7">
                    approximately <m>904\,\text{L}.</m>
                </p>
            </answer>
            <solution>
                <p xml:id="auto_b3jrp4iw">Radius <m>r=0.6\,\text{m}.</m> Volume: <m>V=\tfrac{4}{3}\pi r^3=\tfrac{4}{3}\times3.14\times0.6^3\approx\tfrac{4}{3}\times3.14\times0.216\approx0.904\,\text{m}^3</m>, about <m>904\,\text{L}.</m></p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="ex-vol-pyramid-roof">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_vmnx7vcm">
                    A small store has a square pyramidal roof under which we want to store grain. The base of the pyramidal roof is 4 m by 4 m and its height 2.5 m. Estimate the volume of the the space under the roof  in cubic metres.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p xml:id="auto_k0kv627r">Approximately 13.3 m^3 (≈ 13,333 L)</p>
            </answer>
            <solution>
                <p xml:id="auto_2tbdpf4b">Volume of a pyramid: <m>V=\tfrac{1}{3}Bh</m> where <m>B</m> is base area. Here <m>B=4\times4=16\,\text{m}^2</m> and <m>h=2.5\,\text{m}</m>, so <m>V=\tfrac{1}{3}\times16\times2.5=\tfrac{40}{3}\approx13.33\,\text{m}^3.</m></p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="ex-vol-sand-pile">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_axmcdwoe">
                    A conical sand pile has base radius 1.2 m and height 0.8 m. Estimate the volume of sand in cubic metres and litres. (Use <m>\pi\approx3.14</m>.)
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p xml:id="auto_ivlzkcsq">About 1.21 m^3 (≈ 1,210 L)</p>
            </answer>
            <solution>
                <p xml:id="auto_doi2hbje">Volume of a cone: <m>V=\tfrac{1}{3}\pi r^2 h</m>. With <m>r=1.2, h=0.8</m> we get <m>V=\tfrac{1}{3}\times3.14\times1.2^2\times0.8\approx1.206\,\text{m}^3</m>, about <m>1{,}206\,\text{L}.</m></p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

    </exercises>

    

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Differentiation Strategies</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_0tazx9b2">
            <alert>For Struggling Learners:</alert>
            <ul>
                <li xml:id="auto_9e7wov1z"><p xml:id="auto_yciqwccr">Provide a formula reference card for each shape.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_1uc5rp59"><p xml:id="auto_e4p63ze6">Break down unit conversion into separate steps.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_tl14cize"><p xml:id="auto_df6fnadt">Use simpler numbers (whole numbers, easy decimals).</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_oqx49sf6"><p xml:id="auto_llnhq7oo">Allow calculator use for all calculations.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_k2wxlbzs"><p xml:id="auto_hht948eo">Provide a worked example template to follow.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_bx926zju"><p xml:id="auto_ha7nn3lq">Focus on rectangular boxes and cylinders only.</p></li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_7yt8yu7m">
            <alert>For Advanced Learners:</alert>
            <ul>
                <li xml:id="auto_40cqifxn"><p xml:id="auto_2axlnvl2">Introduce frustum and composite solid problems.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_pv2zhyan"><p xml:id="auto_3srcw168">Challenge with cost calculations (price per litre).</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_kmlpwhht"><p xml:id="auto_ljazcg2m">Explore optimisation (which shape holds the most for a given surface area).</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_2pahezvn"><p xml:id="auto_ubyqj9kf">Investigate irregular shapes using approximation.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_a5yhf4a4"><p xml:id="auto_heuk6ovm">Connect to density and mass calculations.</p></li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_sh2xpsxl">
            <alert>Extension Activity <mdash/> Household Water Storage Project:</alert> A family of 5 needs 50 litres of water per person per day. Calculate how many litres are needed for one week. Choose container shapes (rectangular tank, cylindrical drum, or combination) and determine what dimensions would provide enough storage. Compare which shape is most efficient (holds the most water for the least material). Present the design with calculations.
        </p>
    </axiom>

